  "prompt": "Why is big G used in the formula of force?",
  "response": "In the formula for gravitational force, \"big G\" (G) represents the universal gravitational constant. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Universal Constant:\n- G is a fundamental physical constant that is the same everywhere in the universe\n- Its value is approximately 6.674 \u00d7 10^-11 N(m/kg)\u00b2\n\n2. Purpose in Gravitational Force Formula:\n- Helps calculate the gravitational attraction between two objects\n- Used in Newton's law of universal gravitation: F = G(m1 * m2)/r\u00b2\n- Connects mass, distance, and gravitational force\n\n3. Significance:\n- Provides a proportionality factor that relates masses and distance to gravitational force\n- Helps standardize gravitational force calculations across different scenarios\n\n4. Historical Context:\n- Determined experimentally by Henry Cavendish in 1798\n- Represents the strength of gravitational interaction between masses\n\n5. Dimensional Analysis:\n- Ensures the units of the gravitational force equation are consistent\n- Allows calculation of force when masses and distance are known\n\nThe universal gravitational constant G is crucial in understanding gravitational interactions between objects in physics and astronomy.",
